--- PART 2: ALGEBRAIC CONNECTION ---
For chords a,b (with 1 <= a < b <= m):
Zero-sum triple in QR using chords a,b exists iff
there is a QR element c such that one of:
  +a + b + c = 0,  +a + b - c = 0 (i.e., c = a+b or c = -(a+b))
  +a - b + c = 0,  +a - b - c = 0 (i.e., c = b-a or c = a-b)
  -a + b + c = 0,  -a + b - c = 0 (same as above by symmetry)
  -a - b + c = 0,  -a - b - c = 0 (i.e., c = a+b, same as first)

So the conditions reduce to:
  (a+b) mod p in QR, OR (b-a) mod p in QR, OR
  (p-a-b) mod p in QR, OR (a-b) mod p in QR

Since QR is closed under p-x at p=3 mod 4 (chi(-1)=-1 means x in QR iff p-x in QNR),
wait - chi(-1) = (-1)^{(p-1)/2} = -1 at p=3 mod 4. So -x is QNR when x is QR.
Therefore (p-a-b) in QR iff -(a+b) in QR iff (a+b) in QNR.
And (a-b) in QR iff (b-a) in QNR.

Conditions for zero-sum triple using chords a,b:
  (a+b) in QR  OR  (b-a) in QR  (the other two are complementary)

